00:29.821 --> 00:33.532
Man: Thirty years ago, my wife and l
purchased a liquor license.

00:33.700 --> 00:38.162
Then we had the liquor store up
and running by Christmas.

00:38.329 --> 00:41.999
We poured our heart and soul in it.
And then, lo and behold,

00:42.125 --> 00:44.960
l get a knock on my door
one night, l'm at the house,

00:45.128 --> 00:48.630
my wife's down at the liquor store
working, and it was Kevin Weeks

00:48.798 --> 00:52.801
and Whitey Bulger at the door,
and l didn't know,

00:52.969 --> 00:54.053
what the hell do they want?

00:56.056 --> 00:59.058
"You got a problem."
l said, "l don't... what problem?"

00:59.184 --> 01:02.311
He says, "Listen,
we were hired to kill you."

01:02.520 --> 01:04.229
l'm like, what?

01:04.355 --> 01:06.690
He said, you got to understand,
the other liquor stores,

01:06.858 --> 01:09.234
they hired us to kill you.

01:10.278 --> 01:12.613
l just couldn't believe it,
l didn't know what to even think,

01:12.822 --> 01:15.157
l was dumbfounded.
Actually, l froze.

01:15.408 --> 01:18.702
He said, "But what we're going to do
instead of that, we're just going to

01:18.828 --> 01:22.706
become your partners." l said, "No,
you're not becoming my partners."

01:22.874 --> 01:27.961
And then, Bulger's right there.
He's just staring at me,

01:28.129 --> 01:33.175
and just grinding his teeth like,
"You don't understand,

01:33.384 --> 01:35.052
we're taking
the fucking liquor store."

01:35.303 --> 01:38.055
l was like, "lt's not for sale."
He said, "l'll fucking kill you.

01:38.223 --> 01:42.893
l'll stab you, and then l'll kill you."
l'm like, Holy Jesus.

01:43.103 --> 01:47.314
And then they pulled out a gun.
l was like, "Oh, fuck."

01:49.150 --> 01:51.068
They picked up my kid.

01:51.236 --> 01:53.320
Daughter was a year.

01:53.488 --> 01:54.696
He said, "lt would be terrible

01:54.864 --> 01:59.368
for this kid to grow up without a father."
l was like... and l melted.

02:01.704 --> 02:02.704
Nothing you can do.

02:07.252 --> 02:09.461
Ever since that day,
l've never been the same.

02:09.628 --> 02:14.591
l couldn't protect my own children.
As a man, that just took me away.

02:14.759 --> 02:18.428
And l'm not over it yet.
l won't be over, and maybe l'll never

02:18.638 --> 02:21.640
get over it, but l surely can't wait
to get in front of that court,

02:21.766 --> 02:24.935
on that stand and testify
against that. 30 years ago,

02:25.145 --> 02:27.396
he scared me to death, he don't
scare me to death no more.

02:29.983 --> 02:33.235
Woman: After 16 years, the FBl
finally has its man.

02:33.319 --> 02:37.197
Boston mob boss James Whitey Bulger
was captured in Southern California.

02:37.365 --> 02:40.909
Man: ...along with his longtime girlfriend,
Catherine Elizabeth Greig.

02:41.077 --> 02:43.579
The 83-year-old
is accused of drug trafficking,

02:43.746 --> 02:47.541
extortion and murder, all while
working as an FBl informant.

02:47.709 --> 02:49.710
He was on the lam for 16 years.

02:51.629 --> 02:55.257
l never committed a crime in the
16 years that l was with Catherine.

02:55.466 --> 02:57.426
My whole life changed
when l was with her.

02:57.594 --> 03:02.389
l turned and become very,
very human, l guess you'd say it.

03:02.557 --> 03:06.852
And l love the woman intensely.
When l was captured, l told them,

03:07.020 --> 03:10.898
"lf you people," l says, "will let Catherine
go, l'll plead guilty to all crimes."

03:11.107 --> 03:14.818
"Any crime," l says, "innocent
or guilty. Youse can execute me,

03:15.028 --> 03:17.654
you can give me life sentence,
you can do whatever youse want,

03:17.906 --> 03:21.283
but l want her to be free."
And l meant it, and l mean it today.

03:21.492 --> 03:22.993
lf they said to me,
"Plead guilty, and we'll

03:23.203 --> 03:26.163
let her go free and shut your mouth,"
l would do it.

03:45.058 --> 03:48.894
Woman: lt's been a long time coming.
After 16 years on the lam

03:49.062 --> 03:53.398
and two years in custody,
the criminal trial of James Whitey Bulger

03:53.566 --> 03:57.319
began today at the John J. Moakley
courthouse in South Boston,

03:57.528 --> 04:00.656
just blocks away from
Whitey's former home turf.

04:00.740 --> 04:02.074
( sirens wailing )

04:02.242 --> 04:05.035
Man: This is what it looked like here
at the courthouse earlier this morning.

04:05.203 --> 04:08.580
A police escort and several black
SUVs roll up to federal court.

04:08.748 --> 04:11.667
Behind the tinted windows,
James Whitey Bulger,

04:11.834 --> 04:15.462
who is back in Boston to face
19 charges of murder

04:15.588 --> 04:19.675
in the same city he's accused
of terrorizing as a gang boss.

04:19.841 --> 04:22.052
Man 2: Some of the victims' families
also arriving today,

04:22.220 --> 04:25.847
hoping to see justice done
after waiting almost 30 years.

04:26.015 --> 04:28.308
l'm happy that this is about to start.
lt's been a long wait.

04:28.518 --> 04:31.853
A really, really long wait in time.
So, l'll see youse when l get out.

04:31.980 --> 04:34.064
How are you going to
feel being in there?

04:34.232 --> 04:36.817
l don't know.
Sick to my stomach now,

04:37.026 --> 04:39.611
l can only imagine
when l get in there.

04:39.737 --> 04:42.739
Woman: Prosecutors describe
James Whitey Bulger as the center

04:42.949 --> 04:45.867
of mayhem and murder in Boston
for 30 years,

04:46.119 --> 04:49.121
as the boss of Boston's
notorious Winter Hill Gang.

04:49.289 --> 04:52.291
A man so dangerous that he
joined Osama Bin Laden

04:52.417 --> 04:54.960
at the top of the FBl's
Most Wanted list.

04:55.169 --> 04:59.339
lt was the gang that ran amok. You
have people who were being extorted,

04:59.507 --> 05:02.759
who talked of having shotgun
barrels stuck in their mouths,

05:02.927 --> 05:05.679
of machine guns
pointed at their groin.

05:05.888 --> 05:09.891
Boeri: Body bags shown them
before Bulger shakes them down.

05:10.059 --> 05:12.394
lt was absolute terror.

05:12.603 --> 05:18.150
Back then, 70s, 80s, people
were missing every day, bang.

05:19.027 --> 05:21.236
He didn't come home,
he's a dead man.

05:21.321 --> 05:22.988
They're never going to find him.

05:23.156 --> 05:26.408
Brian Howell. Dead.
Michael Donahue. Dead.

05:26.576 --> 05:28.493
Bodies were being,
left and right.

05:28.661 --> 05:31.163
And were all involved

05:31.289 --> 05:36.543
in this circle of shit
in South Boston.

05:38.504 --> 05:40.839
Man: And you have a fascination
with Whitey Bulger

05:40.965 --> 05:46.261
as a Robin Hood figure, this elusive,
Houdini-like crime boss,

05:46.429 --> 05:49.139
whose younger brother, Bill Bulger,
was Senate President,

05:49.307 --> 05:51.725
the most powerful
politician in Massachusetts.

05:51.893 --> 05:54.561
All this stuff that was sort of
magical about him

05:54.729 --> 05:58.023
that made him seem
beyond the reach of law enforcement.

05:58.191 --> 06:02.152
Man: There were over 25 years
where James Bulger ruled

06:02.320 --> 06:04.738
the organized crime world.
He was never charged

06:04.989 --> 06:06.198
with even a misdemeanor.

06:06.449 --> 06:10.660
The Department of Justice
did nothing to prosecute him.

06:10.828 --> 06:13.997
Woman: Whitey was the guy
that got away. Whitey was the guy

06:14.248 --> 06:17.793
out in the wind, thumbing his nose,
"Ha-ha, l won," for years.

06:17.919 --> 06:21.296
So today is huge. l mean,
l think that, you know, what...

06:21.464 --> 06:26.927
There's so many people who never
thought this day would ever happen.

06:27.220 --> 06:31.223
Man: James Whitey Bulger fled Boston
in late 1994, as federal agents

06:31.391 --> 06:34.101
were about to arrest him
in connection with 19 killings,

06:34.268 --> 06:39.231
racketeering, and other crimes that
spanned the early 1970s to mid 1980s.

06:39.399 --> 06:41.983
Man 2: He fled after being
tipped off by an FBl agent.

06:42.151 --> 06:43.693
He was about to be indicted.

06:43.861 --> 06:47.155
Woman: Bulger's role as an FBl
informant is central to this trial.

06:47.323 --> 06:49.616
Man 3: Now he'll face justice
in the same city

06:49.784 --> 06:52.661
many say he ran with an iron fist.

07:08.928 --> 07:12.639
l'll be honest with you,
l have today's date, June 12th.

07:13.683 --> 07:15.350
But lately, l couldn't...

07:16.936 --> 07:19.312
The past few days,
l couldn't tell you what,

07:19.522 --> 07:22.274
and it's the God's truth,
l couldn't tell you

07:22.567 --> 07:27.070
if it was Sunday, Monday,
Friday. lt's... l was...

07:27.238 --> 07:29.030
Man: How come?

07:29.198 --> 07:33.994
My head's been so twisted over all this.
You know, it's like... surreal.

07:34.287 --> 07:37.414
You know, it's...
it's happening.

07:38.666 --> 07:44.337
Whitey killed my sister.
She was looked upon as a good person.

07:44.505 --> 07:49.801
She'd come in the room and she'd,
she'd light it up.

07:50.011 --> 07:53.513
"Hey." You know, "Everybody..."
You know, it's...

07:53.681 --> 07:56.433
He had no right to take her life.

07:59.270 --> 08:04.274
And he took her teeth out,
her hands, and...

08:09.906 --> 08:13.617
Woman: Mike was killed 30 years ago.

08:14.494 --> 08:19.456
But, you know, l think when you
lose somebody, there's no time.

08:19.749 --> 08:22.167
Sometimes it just seems
like yesterday.

08:22.335 --> 08:25.003
l don't think he should've
died when he died.

08:25.171 --> 08:27.380
He had too much to live for.

08:27.548 --> 08:30.425
You know, the day he was killed,
he was looking for my son Michael

08:30.551 --> 08:33.636
to take him with him.
But, he was down the park,

08:33.804 --> 08:35.013
and he couldn't find him.

08:35.181 --> 08:37.307
So l said, just, you know,
"Just go without him."

08:37.475 --> 08:43.313
Thank God, you know. l guess there's
a reason for everything, you know.

08:49.445 --> 08:51.029
Davis: Did you get a haircut?

08:52.406 --> 08:54.115
Get over here,
l want to introduce you.

08:54.283 --> 08:55.992
Look it, l didn't know l was
supposed to get all dressed up.

08:56.160 --> 08:58.161
- l just got a shirt on.
- Jesus Christ.

08:58.329 --> 09:00.580
- Today, l feel fantastic.
- Man: How come?

09:00.748 --> 09:03.416
Well, 30 years ago, they
tormented me, and it's been

09:03.584 --> 09:08.046
30 years of torment, and now it's
coming to an end.

09:08.297 --> 09:10.840
Thank God he's behind bars.

09:11.133 --> 09:14.678
My father always told me that good
will always triumph over evil.

09:14.929 --> 09:18.223
Even if it takes a long time.
And that's just what l'm here for.

09:18.432 --> 09:20.267
- We don't forget.
- Rakes: No.

09:20.434 --> 09:22.227
- No.
- You know what l mean?

09:24.230 --> 09:29.192
The only kind of comfort l get
through this is talking with him.

09:29.318 --> 09:31.278
You know, me and Steve
meet every morning,

09:31.445 --> 09:33.363
just about every morning for coffee.

09:33.531 --> 09:35.156
That's why Steve and l,
we have something in common,

09:35.366 --> 09:39.160
this psychotic individual.
We're going to bring justice,

09:39.328 --> 09:40.996
it has to be done.

09:41.163 --> 09:46.001
Finally payback.
As nervous as l am, exciting,

09:46.210 --> 09:50.547
the adrenaline is pumping, l just can't,
l can't believe l'm finally here.

09:50.715 --> 09:54.801
l finally get to stop.
l'll have my day, my time.

09:54.969 --> 09:56.678
Woman: Gentleman, let me ask you
just to say a few words

09:56.971 --> 09:58.805
as you're going in,
what your thoughts are.

09:59.015 --> 10:03.351
Anxious. The day has come.

10:03.519 --> 10:05.353
Man: What are you going to be
thinking as you look at him

10:05.521 --> 10:07.314
in that courtroom today?

10:07.481 --> 10:10.442
Well, you know, 30 years ago,
l'd never look at him.

10:10.610 --> 10:12.819
Now l can't wait to look him
right in the eyes.

10:12.987 --> 10:17.365
Reporter on radio: lt's day one of one of
the most anticipated trials in decades.

10:17.533 --> 10:19.784
Reporter 2: Cameras should've been
allowed in the courtroom.

10:19.952 --> 10:21.995
Obviously, in federal court,
they are not allowed.

10:22.163 --> 10:24.748
Female reporter: For the people of
Boston, this case is about justice.

10:24.957 --> 10:27.584
lt is about redemption,
it is about retribution.

10:27.835 --> 10:31.212
Opening statements in the trial
of James Whitey Bulger.

10:31.380 --> 10:33.340
Reporter 3: The Assistant US Attorney,
Brian Kelly, telling jurors.

10:33.507 --> 10:37.093
Kelly: "He did the dirty work himself,
because he was a hands-on killer

10:37.345 --> 10:40.263
who ran amok in the city of Boston
for almost 30 years.

10:40.431 --> 10:43.099
Bulger was deeply involved
in the distribution of drugs

10:43.267 --> 10:44.601
in the South Boston area.

10:44.727 --> 10:47.354
Bulger was one of the biggest
informants in Boston.

10:47.521 --> 10:50.440
Bulger routinely met
with FBl agent John Connolly

10:50.566 --> 10:53.443
and gave him information
to protect himself,

10:53.611 --> 10:55.987
or get the competitive edge
that he wanted."

10:56.155 --> 10:58.198
Reporter 3: He then showed the jury
pictures of each

10:58.366 --> 11:00.742
of the 19 people
investigators say Bulger killed.

11:00.910 --> 11:03.536
Woman: They described victims,
former friends, associates,

11:03.663 --> 11:06.831
girlfriends, all killed
and buried in secret graves.

11:06.999 --> 11:11.044
Some relatives in court listening
choked up when they heard that.

11:11.212 --> 11:13.213
Woman 2: The government,
ending its opening statements

11:13.381 --> 11:16.633
by slowly, dramatically,
reading off the names

11:16.926 --> 11:19.302
of the 19 alleged murder victims.

11:19.428 --> 11:23.765
Man: Bucky Barrett, Roger Wheeler,
Brian Halloran, Michael Donahue,

11:23.891 --> 11:27.852
John Callahan, Deborah Davis,
and Deborah Hussey.

11:28.020 --> 11:30.105
Kelly: This is not
a traditional murder case.

11:30.272 --> 11:33.191
lt's a racketeering charge.
And within the racketeering charge,

11:33.359 --> 11:36.069
there are multiple predicate crimes
that we have to prove.

11:36.195 --> 11:40.240
We have to prove at least two of them.
And Bulger is charged with 33

11:40.408 --> 11:43.827
separate predicate crimes.
19 separate murders,

11:43.994 --> 11:46.955
multiple extortions,
drug dealing, gambling.

11:47.123 --> 11:48.957
And of those,
we have to prove at least two

11:49.125 --> 11:50.750
beyond a reasonable doubt,
and we have to prove

11:50.918 --> 11:53.211
that Bulger was part of
this criminal enterprise

11:53.379 --> 11:57.465
that was committing
all these crimes for 30 years.

11:57.633 --> 12:00.510
Man: Defense attorney J.W. Carney
stunned the courtroom, admitting

12:00.678 --> 12:04.222
for the first time that Bulger was
involved in drug trafficking.

12:04.390 --> 12:07.892
Carney: James Bulger was involved
in drug dealing. He was involved in

12:08.060 --> 12:11.479
bookmaking, loan sharking.
These crimes are what he did.

12:11.647 --> 12:13.898
Man: But he poked holes
in government witnesses.

12:14.066 --> 12:16.359
Woman: Carney tried to paint
a picture of Bulger associates

12:16.527 --> 12:19.779
turned government witnesses,
John Martorano, Kevin Weeks,

12:19.905 --> 12:22.574
and Steven Flemmi
as the real murderers

12:22.742 --> 12:24.951
who just pinned their crimes
on his client.

12:25.119 --> 12:29.205
Boeri: The defense said, all those three
witnesses' testimony was purchased.

12:29.373 --> 12:31.374
They were murderous thugs
whose testimony

12:31.542 --> 12:33.960
was purchased by sparing them
the death penalty,

12:34.170 --> 12:37.672
cutting their prison sentence,
and offering them all sorts of incentives.

12:37.840 --> 12:40.884
Given these three individuals,
given their backgrounds,

12:41.135 --> 12:45.680
given their character, would you believe
them beyond a reasonable doubt?

12:46.015 --> 12:48.183
Woman: Carney denied
that Bulger was an informant.

12:48.350 --> 12:51.519
The evidence will show
that he was never an informant

12:51.645 --> 12:56.065
for John Connolly and the FBl.
You will learn the depth of corruption

12:56.275 --> 12:59.736
in federal law enforcement that
existed during this period.

12:59.862 --> 13:04.949
This was how James Bulger was able
to never, ever be charged.

13:10.122 --> 13:13.833
Boeri: What makes this trial
extraordinary, and really crazy,

13:14.001 --> 13:16.795
the defense is defending him
from an assertion that he was

13:16.962 --> 13:20.799
an informant, even though it's not
a charge. And so what seems crazy

13:20.966 --> 13:23.426
is the government has
gotten sucked into this as well,

13:23.594 --> 13:26.679
they're trying to prove that he is,
even though it's totally irrelevant

13:26.847 --> 13:28.014
to his guilt or innocence.

13:28.182 --> 13:32.852
So it's not about guilt or innocence,
it's about his legacy,

13:33.020 --> 13:36.648
of wanting to establish he wasn't
a tout, a rat, an informant,

13:36.816 --> 13:38.274
whatever you want to call it.

13:38.484 --> 13:40.735
( sirens wailing )

13:42.947 --> 13:47.867
Carney: l was as surprised as anyone
when James Whitey Bulger was captured.

13:48.035 --> 13:51.412
ls the government excited about
having Bulger come back?

13:51.580 --> 13:55.875
Some people certainly are.
But there are others, l think,

13:56.043 --> 13:58.002
who have many sleepless nights

13:58.170 --> 14:00.880
about what James Bulger
is going to testify to.

14:02.007 --> 14:05.468
l believe the reason that they are
giving so much protection to Bulger

14:05.636 --> 14:08.304
to transport him from the jail
to the courthouse,

14:08.472 --> 14:11.266
is they are worried about
someone with a sniper rifle

14:11.433 --> 14:15.645
taking him out on the way to court
so that he can't testify.

14:15.813 --> 14:19.732
That's how explosive
his testimony will be.

14:29.368 --> 14:31.953
Man: This is Whitey's world.

14:32.121 --> 14:35.123
You go from Squantum,
where he lived with Cathy...

14:35.291 --> 14:41.254
lt's basically six miles, if you drive
it, up to Castle lsland over there.

14:41.422 --> 14:43.965
That's Southie, where
he did most of his crime.

14:44.133 --> 14:46.342
He murdered people there.
He buried people there.

14:46.510 --> 14:49.637
And he went to sleep there.
So, that's his world.

14:51.223 --> 14:54.434
Man 2: l spent much of my childhood
in South Boston,

14:54.560 --> 14:58.938
and even as a kid, l knew
Whitey Bulger ran the show here.

14:59.106 --> 15:01.149
But Whitey was very lucky.

15:01.317 --> 15:03.693
ln the 1960s, there was
an lrish gang war.

15:03.861 --> 15:06.321
And over 60 people were killed.

15:06.488 --> 15:09.324
But Whitey was in prison.
So he missed all that.

15:09.408 --> 15:11.117
He would've had
a high, high chance

15:11.327 --> 15:15.121
of being a victim of that violence.

15:15.331 --> 15:16.623
When he got out of prison,

15:16.790 --> 15:20.585
Whitey went to Howie Winter, who was
the leader of the Winter Hill Gang,

15:20.753 --> 15:25.632
preeminent non-Mafia gang
in this region. And he said to Howie,

15:25.799 --> 15:28.176
"We got to stop the war in Southie,
too many people are dying,

15:28.469 --> 15:31.846
we're losing money."
Howie was very impressed by Whitey.

15:32.014 --> 15:34.057
And one of the things
that impressed him most

15:34.308 --> 15:36.392
was that Whitey had done time
in Alcatraz.

15:36.560 --> 15:40.396
Now, you know, for you and me,
you know, we like to hand in our resume

15:40.564 --> 15:43.942
and say, "See, l went to Stanford,
l got my MBA at Wharton."

15:44.151 --> 15:47.612
But in that milieu, if you're a wise guy,
you say, "Oh, you went to Alcatraz."

15:47.821 --> 15:50.657
And Howie said
that Whitey came across

15:50.824 --> 15:52.867
as a guy that could be a leader.

15:53.035 --> 15:57.038
So Howie mediates the end
of the war with a rival gang

15:57.247 --> 16:00.166
in South Boston called the Mullens,
in which the Mullens

16:00.292 --> 16:03.294
actually were about to prevail.
And the Mullen's guys think,

16:03.462 --> 16:06.214
you know, they're about to
get the lion's share of everything.

16:06.340 --> 16:10.969
And Howie threw them for a loop,
when he announced that Jimmy Bulger,

16:11.136 --> 16:13.763
he's going to front money for them,
they can put money on the street,

16:14.014 --> 16:17.225
loan shark,
they can do a gambling operation,

16:17.393 --> 16:18.768
but Whitey's going to be in charge.

16:18.936 --> 16:21.270
And the Mullen's guys were going,
"What, are you kidding me?

16:21.438 --> 16:22.438
We were winning."

16:22.606 --> 16:25.650
And Tommy King, who was
a member of the Mullens said,

16:25.776 --> 16:28.194
"We should have killed Whitey
when we had a chance,

16:28.362 --> 16:30.071
because this is going to
come back to bite us."

16:36.495 --> 16:39.539
Man: Southie was great growing up.
Everybody knew everyone.

16:39.707 --> 16:42.083
Everyone watched out for everybody.
lt was great.

16:42.292 --> 16:45.545
You know, we didn't have a lot, but
we had a lot of fun with what we had.

16:45.713 --> 16:47.964
My brothers both went to
