01:18:33.458 --> 01:18:36.252
as a witness and that he can
single-handedly help us

01:18:36.378 --> 01:18:40.506
put away John Connolly
and maybe Jimmy Bulger

01:18:40.716 --> 01:18:42.216
if Jimmy Bulger ever turns up.

01:18:42.384 --> 01:18:45.136
Man: Who did you believe you were
going to be protecting,

01:18:45.303 --> 01:18:47.304
by killing Callahan?

01:18:47.472 --> 01:18:50.766
l was protecting myself,
Whitey Bulger, Stevie Flemmi,

01:18:50.934 --> 01:18:52.476
and John Connolly.

01:18:52.602 --> 01:18:55.354
McDonald: They need John Connolly
to be the scapegoat.

01:18:55.522 --> 01:18:59.024
They've got to have
Connolly as the corrupt agent,

01:18:59.192 --> 01:19:02.111
with respect to all
of what went on in Boston,

01:19:02.279 --> 01:19:05.698
with respect to the top
echelon informant program,

01:19:05.866 --> 01:19:08.075
they have to have someone to blame.

01:19:08.243 --> 01:19:12.538
Why are you prosecuting Connolly
for the Callahan murder,

01:19:12.789 --> 01:19:14.874
when you know
the killer is Martorano,

01:19:15.041 --> 01:19:17.668
the guy who actually
pulled the trigger, for Pete's sake.

01:19:17.794 --> 01:19:19.754
But they convicted John Connolly,

01:19:19.963 --> 01:19:22.631
and then he was sentenced
for 40 years.

01:19:25.886 --> 01:19:30.139
Kelly: Martorano's plea agreement has
been roundly criticized for good reason.

01:19:30.390 --> 01:19:33.017
Most people think he should have
gotten more than 12 years,

01:19:33.185 --> 01:19:35.102
and we're no exception to that view.

01:19:35.270 --> 01:19:40.232
He is in fact a ruthless killer,
but at the time we had no evidence

01:19:40.484 --> 01:19:44.236
of his killing. And when he pled
guilty he not only got more time,

01:19:44.404 --> 01:19:49.575
but he also led to a series of events,
he made cooperation fashionable.

01:19:49.785 --> 01:19:51.994
Man: Mr. Weeks, if you will
come forward, please.

01:19:52.162 --> 01:19:56.290
l was arrested November 17, '99
and they were telling me

01:19:56.458 --> 01:20:00.044
what it came down to,
make it really quick and simple,

01:20:00.253 --> 01:20:02.046
is that it's a race.

01:20:02.214 --> 01:20:04.215
lt's either you or Stevie,
and you're going to get

01:20:04.382 --> 01:20:07.218
the last seat on the bus,
but whichever one of youse

01:20:07.344 --> 01:20:09.678
get up there first to make a deal
with the government

01:20:09.763 --> 01:20:11.388
is going to get the best deal.

01:20:13.099 --> 01:20:15.643
You know, what's Stevie gonna do?
Stevie's gonna give me up,

01:20:15.769 --> 01:20:17.645
and say it was Kevin, and it was
this one and it was that one

01:20:17.813 --> 01:20:19.647
that killed all these people,
it wasn't us.

01:20:19.773 --> 01:20:22.149
You know, here's the bodies.
That's where they put them and stuff.

01:20:22.359 --> 01:20:24.485
l said no, there's no way l'm
taking it up the ass for them.

01:20:24.653 --> 01:20:28.781
So l made the deal first.
l figured you can't rat on a rat.

01:20:28.990 --> 01:20:33.118
Kelly: Kevin Weeks, his plea was
a critical turning point in this case

01:20:33.286 --> 01:20:36.455
because he literally led us
to the bodies, he brought us

01:20:36.623 --> 01:20:40.626
to the burial grounds where we saw
for ourselves Bulger's handiwork.

01:20:41.962 --> 01:20:45.881
Carney: Kevin Weeks, five murders,
he does five years.

01:20:46.091 --> 01:20:50.970
John Martorano, for 20 murders
he got a sentence of 12 years,

01:20:51.096 --> 01:20:54.348
plus they let him keep money,
keep property.

01:20:54.474 --> 01:20:57.560
They got him a waiver of
the death penalty in Oklahoma,

01:20:57.686 --> 01:21:00.646
and a waiver of the death penalty
in Florida.

01:21:00.772 --> 01:21:04.817
They paid his commissary fees
while he was in prison,

01:21:04.985 --> 01:21:09.029
and when he got out,
gave him a $20,000 check.

01:21:09.239 --> 01:21:12.449
Man: A quarter of a million dollar
advance for selling the movie rights

01:21:12.659 --> 01:21:15.870
to his life story,
$110,000 or something advance

01:21:16.037 --> 01:21:17.413
for the book he co-wrote.

01:21:17.581 --> 01:21:20.708
- Man 2: The state calls John Morris.
- Man 3: John Morris, please.

01:21:20.876 --> 01:21:24.378
l would say the most scandalous deal
that the government made

01:21:24.504 --> 01:21:27.423
was with one of their own
and that was John Morris,

01:21:27.591 --> 01:21:30.718
who was John Connolly's
equally corrupt supervisor,

01:21:30.844 --> 01:21:36.140
and who got people killed,
and he got no time, nothing.

01:21:36.349 --> 01:21:39.143
John had told me
that these guys really like you

01:21:39.352 --> 01:21:44.023
and if you ever needed anything
to just ask.

01:21:44.232 --> 01:21:48.360
Man: John Morris is corrupt an FBl
official as one could possibly be,

01:21:48.486 --> 01:21:52.823
not a minute in jail.
He's a wine consultant now.

01:21:53.074 --> 01:21:58.871
l didn't want what happened to me
to happen to other agents.

01:22:00.040 --> 01:22:02.291
Mr. Flemmi, if you'll stand up
and raise your right hand,

01:22:02.459 --> 01:22:03.834
Linda will swear you in.

01:22:04.002 --> 01:22:07.171
Flemmi wound up making his deal
when it was really too late

01:22:07.339 --> 01:22:10.633
to get a good deal, so he wound up
getting a life sentence,

01:22:10.884 --> 01:22:13.969
and now he's become kind of
a professional witness

01:22:14.137 --> 01:22:18.724
for the government, and he's just a
windup doll who says what he believes

01:22:18.892 --> 01:22:21.518
he needs to say so that
the government will give him

01:22:21.686 --> 01:22:25.731
better accommodations in prison,
they'll do little things for him

01:22:25.899 --> 01:22:28.192
that will make the fact that
he's spending the rest of his life

01:22:28.360 --> 01:22:29.818
in prison a little more comfortable.

01:22:29.986 --> 01:22:32.905
He's a pathetic creation
of the system at this point.

01:22:33.073 --> 01:22:35.407
Carney: Do you see the defendant
Mr. Connolly in the courtroom?

01:22:35.575 --> 01:22:39.328
l see him, yes.
Good-looking gentleman,

01:22:39.496 --> 01:22:43.415
he's got a nice haircut.
l know him very well.

01:22:44.376 --> 01:22:47.127
English: These guys, they're all
violating the gangster code.

01:22:47.253 --> 01:22:51.465
They all became some version of
a rat by testifying against people.

01:22:51.591 --> 01:22:54.301
They've all had to reconcile it
in their conscience

01:22:54.469 --> 01:22:58.597
why they did this and they've
all created their little stories,

01:22:58.807 --> 01:23:03.560
their own internal fictions,
of why they've had to do what they do.

01:23:05.730 --> 01:23:08.732
Davis: The state of Massachusetts
has got more rats in it.

01:23:08.900 --> 01:23:14.697
lt's like an infested rat hole.
The lrish mob, every one of them,

01:23:14.864 --> 01:23:19.159
They were stumbling over each other
just to rat.

01:23:19.369 --> 01:23:24.164
They walk around talking big, tough guy
shit, and they're fucking rats.

01:23:24.332 --> 01:23:28.627
The federal court right here,
doesn't it look like a mouse hole?

01:23:28.753 --> 01:23:30.713
( laughing )

01:23:30.797 --> 01:23:32.631
- Man: Good for rats, right?
- Yeah.

01:23:32.841 --> 01:23:34.842
That's where all the rats go.

01:23:39.014 --> 01:23:43.058
Woman: lt was a tense reunion
18 years in the making.

01:23:43.226 --> 01:23:44.977
Finally, James Whitey Bulger

01:23:45.145 --> 01:23:48.188
and his partner Stephen
"The Rifleman" Flemmi were reunited

01:23:48.398 --> 01:23:50.649
as Flemmi took the stand
against Bulger.

01:23:50.817 --> 01:23:54.695
Man: Stephen Flemmi is considered to
be the most critical witness in this case.

01:23:54.863 --> 01:23:57.740
Woman 2: ln rapid-fire succession,
Flemmi described Bulger's

01:23:57.907 --> 01:24:01.368
alleged role in a string of killings
during the 1970s

01:24:01.536 --> 01:24:03.328
when both men were leaders
of the Winter Hill gang.

01:24:03.496 --> 01:24:06.874
Boeri: Flemmi is under pressure,
they're talking about women.

01:24:07.125 --> 01:24:11.503
Bulger is charged with strangling
Deborah Hussey and Debbie Davis.

01:24:11.713 --> 01:24:15.007
The defense is trying to suggest
in fact, it was Flemmi.

01:24:15.258 --> 01:24:17.593
Woman: Hank Brennan grilled
the government witness

01:24:17.761 --> 01:24:21.597
on his sexual relationship with his
then girlfriend's teenage daughter

01:24:21.765 --> 01:24:22.556
Deborah Hussey.

01:24:22.682 --> 01:24:25.726
Woman 2: Flemmi said Deborah Hussey
turned into a drug user

01:24:25.894 --> 01:24:28.145
and an embarrassment,
so they had to kill her.

01:24:29.230 --> 01:24:32.608
Man: At Bulger's trial Friday,
Flemmi said Bulger murdered

01:24:32.776 --> 01:24:35.819
Flemmi's girlfriend Deborah Davis
after the two men decided

01:24:35.945 --> 01:24:37.321
she knew too much.

01:24:37.489 --> 01:24:40.574
Woman: Flemmi claims Bulger
decided Davis had to be killed.

01:24:40.742 --> 01:24:44.328
"l couldn't do it," Flemmi testified.
He said Bulger said,

01:24:44.496 --> 01:24:47.372
"l'll take care of it, l'll do it."
He grabbed her around the throat,

01:24:47.540 --> 01:24:49.500
and strangled her.

01:24:50.460 --> 01:24:55.506
Davis: My sister, Debbie, she dated
Steve Flemmi for over nine years.

01:24:55.757 --> 01:24:58.550
He gave her cars,

01:24:58.676 --> 01:25:02.137
apartments, furniture, jewelry,

01:25:02.305 --> 01:25:04.890
but he would never give her cash.

01:25:05.100 --> 01:25:08.519
You know, he would give her
five, 10 bucks a day, and...

01:25:08.686 --> 01:25:09.937
Cheap prick.

01:25:10.396 --> 01:25:12.439
She loved him, she did love him.

01:25:12.607 --> 01:25:16.276
But at one point she wanted to
get married, she wanted kids.

01:25:16.444 --> 01:25:21.240
My sister wanted kids, and it was
just a rocky road from then on.

01:25:22.033 --> 01:25:24.785
She said, "l'm leaving him,
l'm leaving Steve."

01:25:24.953 --> 01:25:30.582
And l think Whitey
would've taken that as a threat.

01:25:30.708 --> 01:25:33.460
You know, her taking secrets
or whatever with her.

01:25:33.545 --> 01:25:36.255
Man: Flemmi became more
and more defensive,

01:25:36.381 --> 01:25:38.423
and more and more resistant
to the questions

01:25:38.591 --> 01:25:41.385
as Hank Brennan just cut into him.

01:25:41.511 --> 01:25:43.971
Brennan: Were you combining the two
different versions in your testimony

01:25:44.139 --> 01:25:47.724
in front of this jury to make amends
for your inconsistencies, Mr. Flemmi?

01:25:47.851 --> 01:25:50.144
Flemmi: No, it was just probably
an inadvertent mistake on my part.

01:25:50.311 --> 01:25:52.354
Brennan: Another inadvertent mistake
on this case?

01:25:52.522 --> 01:25:54.773
Man: Flemmi is a well-rehearsed
witness now

01:25:54.941 --> 01:25:58.026
because he's testified in three trials
and three civil proceedings.

01:25:58.111 --> 01:26:02.990
ln one court he says that Bulger
strangled her with a rope.

01:26:03.199 --> 01:26:07.077
ln another proceeding he said
he strangled her with his hands.

01:26:07.245 --> 01:26:10.789
And then, in a third proceeding,
he said he thought that Bulger

01:26:10.957 --> 01:26:12.583
had her in a headlock.

01:26:12.750 --> 01:26:15.210
So, at the end of the day,
the inconsistencies, yes,

01:26:15.378 --> 01:26:17.921
they're there, but do they
stop Bulger from being convicted?

01:26:18.089 --> 01:26:22.843
lt certainly does not look like
that is significant enough to do that.

01:26:24.637 --> 01:26:28.307
Carney: Two of the charges against
you, Jim, are that you were involved

01:26:28.558 --> 01:26:32.853
in the murder of
Deborah Hussey and Debbie Davis.

01:26:33.021 --> 01:26:35.772
Did you have any involvement
in those two cases at all?

01:26:35.940 --> 01:26:39.776
Bulger: No way. Those were
Stevie's girlfriends. That's his problem.

01:26:39.986 --> 01:26:42.654
lt had nothing
to do with me, nothing.

01:26:42.822 --> 01:26:47.034
Carney: Do you feel he was fully capable
of committing these by himself?

01:26:47.160 --> 01:26:51.330
Bulger: Christ. When one of the guys
asked him something about a murder,

01:26:51.497 --> 01:26:54.708
he says, well, he's been involved
in so fucking many murders

01:26:54.876 --> 01:26:58.003
he has to say to the guy
"Well, show me the list."

01:26:58.129 --> 01:27:01.590
He needed a list to show him
what murder you're talking about.

01:27:01.758 --> 01:27:06.053
l mean, this guy he is...
l think he's insane, myself, Stevie.

01:27:06.262 --> 01:27:08.889
ln the court he's glaring at me
and l'm looking at him thinking,

01:27:09.015 --> 01:27:11.600
"Christ, Stevie, you're looking at me.
l never said a word against you.

01:27:11.726 --> 01:27:14.311
l'm the injured party."

01:27:14.437 --> 01:27:18.190
But he was like a puppet
for Wyshak, you know.

01:27:19.567 --> 01:27:23.737
Cullen: Whitey Bulger cannot have people
think he murdered those two women.

01:27:23.863 --> 01:27:26.156
And he cannot have people
think he was an informant.

01:27:26.324 --> 01:27:28.116
This is not about getting acquitted,

01:27:28.243 --> 01:27:32.913
this is about changing the narrative
back to the one he spent years cultivating.

01:27:33.039 --> 01:27:35.999
And that narrative
is he is a good bad guy.

01:27:36.167 --> 01:27:40.545
He is a gangster with scruples.
He is a criminal with standards.

01:27:40.713 --> 01:27:44.341
And gangsters with scruples
do not murder women

01:27:44.467 --> 01:27:46.635
and bury them in shallow graves.

01:27:46.803 --> 01:27:50.222
And criminals with standards
don't turn on their friends.

01:27:50.390 --> 01:27:51.682
( sirens wailing )

01:27:51.849 --> 01:27:54.685
Woman: Today could end up being
an extremely interesting day

01:27:54.894 --> 01:27:56.061
at the trial of James Whitey Bulger.

01:27:56.187 --> 01:27:59.439
Woman 2: The big question is whether
or not Whitey himself will take the stand.

01:27:59.607 --> 01:28:01.650
Man: Will James Whitey Bulger
take the stand?

01:28:01.818 --> 01:28:04.027
Everybody's waiting on bated breath
to find out.

01:28:04.195 --> 01:28:06.154
Man 2: My prediction
is he will testify.

01:28:06.406 --> 01:28:08.532
He looks so bad if he doesn't.

01:28:08.700 --> 01:28:10.867
Today's a big day
at the end of the case,

01:28:11.035 --> 01:28:13.912
and l want to let him know that
we're with him and behind him

01:28:13.997 --> 01:28:16.373
no matter what decision he makes.
lf he wants to testify,

01:28:16.541 --> 01:28:19.251
then we're 100 percent behind it.

01:28:19.419 --> 01:28:22.087
lf he doesn't, then l
totally understand as well.

01:28:22.255 --> 01:28:26.800
Boeri: The defense was hoping
to present a defense of immunity,

01:28:26.968 --> 01:28:31.471
that Bulger had been given immunity
by the former US Attorney.

01:28:31.597 --> 01:28:34.349
But before the trial
they got the answer from this judge.

01:28:34.434 --> 01:28:37.185
No, they couldn't, they were
stripped of that defense.

01:28:37.353 --> 01:28:42.316
lt's an interesting argument,
but it is somewhat convenient

01:28:42.483 --> 01:28:46.528
to make the argument because
Jeremiah T. O'Sullivan is dead.

01:28:47.947 --> 01:28:53.243
And there is no written evidence
that we've seen.

01:28:53.411 --> 01:28:56.705
Man: ln courtroom 11 ,
a moment of high drama.

01:28:56.873 --> 01:28:59.499
Whitey's lawyer stood up and said,
"The defense rests."

01:28:59.667 --> 01:29:01.793
Woman: Carney says Bulger
will not take the stand.

01:29:01.961 --> 01:29:05.380
Man 2: When the judge asked if he
made that choice voluntarily,

01:29:05.548 --> 01:29:06.965
he stunned everyone.

01:29:07.133 --> 01:29:09.384
Man 3: "l'm making the choice
involuntarily," Bulger said.

01:29:09.552 --> 01:29:12.012
Woman: Because l feel that l've
been choked off from having

01:29:12.180 --> 01:29:14.973
an opportunity to give
an adequate defense and explain

01:29:15.141 --> 01:29:18.143
about my conversation and agreement
with Jeremiah O'Sullivan.

01:29:18.311 --> 01:29:21.480
Man 4: For my protection of his life,
in return he promised

01:29:21.773 --> 01:29:22.898
to give me immunity."

01:29:23.066 --> 01:29:26.777
Woman: And as Judge Casper said,
she already ruled Bulger's immunity claim

01:29:26.986 --> 01:29:29.112
was inadmissible,
he said defiantly,

01:29:29.280 --> 01:29:31.907
Man 5: "As far as l'm concerned,
l didn't get a fair trial

01:29:32.075 --> 01:29:33.784
and this is a sham."

01:29:33.951 --> 01:29:35.827
Man 6: "And do what youse
want with me.

01:29:35.995 --> 01:29:37.704
That's it.
That's my final word."

01:29:37.872 --> 01:29:41.291
Woman: At that point,
Patricia Donahue rose from her seat,

01:29:41.376 --> 01:29:43.877
and yelled, "You're a coward."

01:29:44.504 --> 01:29:49.132
l yelled out, "You're a coward,"
because that's what he is.

01:29:49.384 --> 01:29:52.928
This man first claims
that he has immunity,

01:29:53.012 --> 01:29:56.223
which he thinks gives him the right
to kill all these people.

01:29:56.432 --> 01:29:59.810
And now he blames an unfair trial

01:30:00.103 --> 01:30:03.772
on the Department of Justice.

01:30:04.524 --> 01:30:07.484
Yet he won't get
on the stand and tell all.

01:30:07.652 --> 01:30:10.028
lf you think that the government
has done wrong by you,

01:30:10.196 --> 01:30:12.906
then get up there and talk about it.

01:30:12.990 --> 01:30:14.282
No comments.

01:30:14.450 --> 01:30:17.285
- How do you feel about your chances?
- No comment.

01:30:17.453 --> 01:30:20.831
Kelly: At the end of the day,
Bulger's immunity claim

01:30:20.998 --> 01:30:24.251
was a ridiculous claim and when
he was given the chance to present it,

01:30:24.585 --> 01:30:30.549
he didn't. His immunity claims were
part of his game of let's pretend.

01:30:30.883 --> 01:30:35.804
Let's pretend l'm going to testify.
Let's pretend l have a license to kill.

01:30:35.930 --> 01:30:38.974
Let's pretend l'm not an informant.

01:30:41.686 --> 01:30:44.396
Brennan: So many people
have the opinion that,

01:30:44.522 --> 01:30:47.232
the idea of whether he was an informant
or not is irrelevant,

01:30:47.358 --> 01:30:50.694
and yet this is the central issue
in this case.

01:30:50.820 --> 01:30:53.363
The reason why the informant status
is important is for a couple of reasons.

01:30:53.573 --> 01:30:56.908
One, the government has an impression
to try and create for the public,

01:30:57.076 --> 01:31:01.204
they want to present a theory
of minimal amount of corruption

01:31:01.372 --> 01:31:05.375
that is quarantined with John Connolly,
based on a rogue agent theory

01:31:05.543 --> 01:31:10.964
and an improper handler who formed
a relationship with James Bulger.

01:31:11.132 --> 01:31:12.841
That's what they've been
trying to do for decades

01:31:12.967 --> 01:31:15.635
in every litigation they've had.
lt's not true.

01:31:15.845 --> 01:31:18.972
The truth is that James Bulger
was not an informant.

01:31:19.182 --> 01:31:21.933
And the reason why it's dangerous
for the Department of Justice

01:31:22.101 --> 01:31:24.352
to recognize the fact
that he wasn't an informant

